{"id":14881395,"mediaExerciseId":"03499e1a-0788-4f95-af36-43896c41181f","exerciseName":"8","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":612375,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":451,"solutions":[{"id":5992532,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"We are asked to evaluate the beta and capital asset pricing model (CAPM) in this exercise. \n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":63,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/d1f456e7d3311308190da9bc101b0655/263ca4b2907b03b6bf1ed4cd9b942d66/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/d1f456e7d3311308190da9bc101b0655/263ca4b2907b03b6bf1ed4cd9b942d66/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A **security's beta** indicates the volatility compared to the overall market. This is the predicted degree of change over securities for a 1% change in market portfolio expected excess.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/d1f456e7d3311308190da9bc101b0655/08d786eb29217f8b56d18ee1bae46f95/lateximg_large.png","width":994},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/d1f456e7d3311308190da9bc101b0655/08d786eb29217f8b56d18ee1bae46f95/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**The beta of a risky asset could be zero**. If a security's beta is zero, the capital cost of an investment should be the risk-free interest rate.\n\nThis is because the capital cost of an investment is computed by multiplying beta by the market risk premium of the investment. The cost of capital will then be calculated by adding the result to the risk-free interest rate.\n\nIf the beta of an investment is zero, regardless of the market risk premium, the outcome will always be zero.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":256,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/d1f456e7d3311308190da9bc101b0655/9e1a819f265df949d386410c15947216/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":128,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/d1f456e7d3311308190da9bc101b0655/9e1a819f265df949d386410c15947216/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"A negative beta may be associated with a risky asset. However, **this necessitates a low expected return since it decreases total portfolio risk when added to a well-diversified portfolio**. This implies that the return will be lower than the risk-free rate.\n\nEven with its significance as a diversifying tool, a negative beta asset would have a negative risk premium. A negative beta is an assurance against an earnings volatility that has a negative impact on the entirety of the portfolio.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":256,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/d1f456e7d3311308190da9bc101b0655/f3cb61bd03a2d7ed00dced28f7e10353/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":128,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/d1f456e7d3311308190da9bc101b0655/f3cb61bd03a2d7ed00dced28f7e10353/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"0919e49d-b8fc-4712-a3bf-557f0f287cd3","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881396,"exerciseName":"9","page":451,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"5bbdc3d0-b3d2-4608-a741-d4e45d20988a","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-critical-thinking-questions-9-5bbdc3d0-b3d2-4608-a741-d4e45d20988a"},{"id":14881397,"exerciseName":"10","page":451,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"9f52d57a-8a60-4095-a6ca-80a8ab404c1d","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-critical-thinking-questions-10-9f52d57a-8a60-4095-a6ca-80a8ab404c1d"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881394,"exerciseName":"7","page":451,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"cd35ddb5-17f0-4278-beec-032340343b12","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-critical-thinking-questions-7-cd35ddb5-17f0-4278-beec-032340343b12"},{"id":14881393,"exerciseName":"6","page":451,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"00549af8-508b-4257-87c7-51f6697b20cb","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-critical-thinking-questions-6-00549af8-508b-4257-87c7-51f6697b20cb"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-critical-thinking-questions-8-03499e1a-0788-4f95-af36-43896c41181f"}